          'US National Electrical Code (NEC) wire color standards govern conductor identification in the US: Black = ungrounded (hot) conductor, single-phase. For multi-wire circuits, black, red, and blue identify the three hot conductors. White or gray = grounded conductor (neutral). Green, green with yellow stripe, or bare copper = Equipment Grounding Conductor (EGC). These colors are mandatory for permanent wiring. In control wiring (inside equipment), manufacturers may deviate, but most follow IEC 60446: blue for neutral, green/yellow for PE, brown or black for live.',
          'Terminal numbering on wiring diagrams: terminal strips are labeled with identifiers like TB1 (Terminal Block 1) and individual terminal numbers (TB1-5 means Terminal Block 1, terminal 5). Component terminals follow standard conventions — relay coils show A1 and A2 terminals; relay contacts use numbered positions (11/12 for NC, 13/14 for NO). On the relay schematic shown, S2 (normally-closed button) controls K2 relay (ABB CR-M coil at A1/A2). K2 contacts (labeled K2.3) at terminals 12/14 control indicators H9 and H10. This terminal numbering appears on every professional wiring diagram.',
          'Reading a wiring diagram step-by-step: (1) Identify the power supply and polarity (top rail = +24VDC in the relay diagram). (2) Trace each conductor by color and wire number. (3) Follow from the source through each component to the return path. (4) Use the component cross-reference table (if provided) to find where relay K2 contacts appear on other drawing sheets — relay coils and their associated contacts are often drawn on different pages. (5) Verify your trace against the schematic logic to confirm the circuit behaves as expected.',
